speech.p:
Do I understand the Secretary of State to repudiate the statement made by the Under-Secretary at an official luncheon, from which I quote these few words:
Drawings were sent to us for approval. Over the door the architect had drawn two large nude male recumbent figures. The Secretary of State and I looked at the figures closely and we looked at each other closely, and then we gave an order to the architect that either the figures were to be put in an alert posture or removed";
and would it not be better for the Secretary of State not to meddle in such matters, but to leave it to the Royal Fine Art Commission?
